SOC Home Lab Upgrade: ntopng Traffic Visibility Layer (Docker + pfSense Integration)
As part of my home SOC lab expansion, I deployed ntopng in a Docker container on a Lenovo ThinkCentre Linux server to enhance real-time network visibility across the environment.
The setup is integrated with my existing pfSense firewall, where traffic flows (NetFlow/sFlow/UDP) are forwarded from pfSense to ntopng via the eth0 interface. This enables deep packet flow analysis, host identification, and application-level traffic monitoring across all network segments.
Key Improvements
- Real-time network flow monitoring and visualisation
- Enhanced detection of unusual traffic patterns and lateral movement
- Improved visibility of LAN/WiFi/IoT device behavior
- Containerised deployment using Docker for easy scaling and isolation
- Direct integration with pfSense for centralised traffic export

This upgrade significantly strengthens the SOC lab’s network observability layer, complementing existing tools like Wazuh SIEM, TheHive, Cortex, MISP, and Suricata IDS/IPS.
